<font color="#FF0000">COMMUNISM IS DYING TOM GUO!</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jun 25 11:56:41 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
To Tao Guo:<br><br>
On November 8, 1967, a reinforced North Vietnamese Army (NVA) battalion attacked refugee settlements at Duc Duc  and Dai Loc, 20 miles southwest of Da Nang. The highly trained communist soldier equipped with Chinese made AK-47's and Russian equipment destroyed over 700 homes and killed over two hundred civilians. I was then serving as a machine gunner with India Company 3/7 1st Marine Division assigned to guard Liberty Bridge and what we called the rocket belt from where the enemy would rocket DaNang with Communist made Rockets. One company of Marines responded less then 1/3 of the enemy force we faced. We caught the enemy battalion in a cross fire and within a few hours had totally destroying its command structure, its highly trained Sappers platoon (Communist Trained Terrorist) and had taken over 90 prisoners. Before we secured that area when the enemy knew they would soon be captured or destroyed, they turned against the civilian population, killing dozens of women, old men and children. They then forced the civilians to run with them as they fired upon us or used them as shields. That was the first time I had personally seen the destruction and total disregard for human life by communist forces. <br><br>
Among the bodies we found which had not been removed from the battle scene were NVA soldiers dressed like villagers, like Viet Cong and popular force soldiers (friendly forces).  Among the dead in battle scenes later during my combat tour of Vietnam (May 30, 1968) were Communist soldiers from Mainland China. They carried weapons, wore Chinese Uniforms and their identification cards showed they were from China. They were taller and lighter then the NVA soldier and it was evident they were in charge.  I personally captured one who when comforted threw down his brand new communist made Ak-47 rifle which he had never fired.  He was turned over to our intelligence and all this information has remained buried. America is now, barely becoming public knowledge. President Johnson and others knew what and who we were fighting but did not have the guts to fight a war when he was surrounded by communist sympathizers at home. <br><br>
It was our country, America that send us to Vietnam and as a Marine my job was to kill Communist soldiers. That is what a Marine is trained to do. I went there to kill them and to come back alive;  I did both. I do not know if I ever killed a Viet Cong.  I do know that I killed many North Vietnamese Communist soldiers, individuals that were trained and supplied by the Soviet Union and Communist China.  That was my job as a United States Marine, to kill Communist soldiers and that is what I did. <br><br>
While we never lost a battle against this worthy foe, because the NVA were well trained we lost Vietnam not on the battlefields of Southeast Asia but to the liberal communist propaganda that effectively influenced public opinion back home. When I returned home I felt betrayed  because the American people had been effectively deceived and others choose instead to remain silent and because of this most American fighting men that served our country with pride and honor and who knew who we were fighting choose instead to also remain silent.<br>
However, American today is waking up and beginning to realize that we really have not lost Vietnam. The inner struggle for independence is still striving within that country. They hunger for the freedom we gave them a taste of and that spirit for independence is still alive today in Vietnam, North Korea and China.<br>
 What we need to realize is like Korea, Vietnam was only a step toward the elimination of communism and in this, we were effective. Had we had a commander in Chief with Guts every Marine I knew was willing to march into Hanoi at a moment's notice. The truth is we fought that war with our hands tied behind us.<br><br>
Someone once asked me if I regretted having fought in Viet Nam. No, I do not regret it. I would not give up that experience for anything in the world.  We fought, not for a dream that was unobtainable, but for the idea of democracy, we fought against Communist aggression and for the type of life that we honestly believed in.  We believed that liberty and justice was for all.  We felt honored to have served our country, to have been given the opportunity to help others, to try to obtain the same freedom we enjoyed. I was fortunate to have been given the opportunity in life to be more than just a witness in history.  We will never see battles again as we did in Viet Nam. If we failed, it was not because we did not do our duty, it was because others entrusted with higher responsibilities failed to do theirs. <br><br>
COOK BARELA, Riverside, California<br>
